    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb-j). Stands inventoried and mapped from the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006), San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005) contain many coastal sage scrub species. Stands have been sampled on San Clemente, Santa Catalina, Santa Cruz, and Santa Rosa Islands (Rodriguez et al. 2017). Stands at Torrey Pines State Reserve are adjacent to both coastal scrub alliances such as <i>Artemisia californica</i> and <i>Encelia californica</i> and chaparral in the <i>Xylococcus bicolor</i> alliance.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> This alliance has expanded its range substantially since the 1930s (Taylor 2004), most likely because of its ability to withstand disturbance such as increased fire return intervals. Composition of <i>Rhus integrifolia </i>stands are also changing because of increasing cover of invasive plants such as <i>Pennisetum setaceum</i>. </div>
</div>

    

    

